{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_beiderbecke_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280657426/1923111701/0370.xml":{"full_text":"MELLON mm\nBIG MOTOR\nBusiness Expansion in Scores\nof Lines Hinges on\nPossible Changes.\nBV J. C. HOYLE.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nN\u2019EW YORK. November 17.\u2014Future\nplans of scores of industries are\nhanging on the tall of the Mellon tax\nrevision kite.\nBankers, manufacturers, merchants\nand Industrial leader* have extended\na remarkable approval of the pro\nposal. declaring: that Its adoption\nwould set new blood coursing\nthrough the arteries of commerce and\nIndustry. They are not however,\ncounting their chickens until Con\ngress and the President have hatched\nthe Mellon egg. Many plans for ex\npansion In 1924 therefore are held In\nabeyance.\nOpposition Expected.\nIndications aro that tho Mellon\nv proposal will not lack for opponents.\nSome of those against the measure\ntake the stand that the revision the\nsecretary outlines would not lift the\nburden of taxation from those least\nable to bear It, but would lighten the\nload of the rich. Still others feed that\nthe majority of the members of Con\ngress are bound by their pledges to\nconstituents to a course of action\nwhich would make reduction of tax\nation Impossible and which might\neven require additional government\nfinancing.\nScores of business enterprises are\ncontemplating expansion In 1924.\nTheir plans undoubtedly would be\nfurthered by adoption of the Mellon\npolicy, but their attitude should the\nproposal meet defeat l\u00bb expressed by\nLewis L. Clarke, president of the\nAmerican Exchange National Bank,\nwho said; \u201cWith taxes as they are\nnew one cannot expect business to\nxpand.'* This stand was confirmed\nby Judge E- H. Gary of tho United\nStates Steel Corporation, who de\nclared the effect of the adoption of\nthe Mellon plan would be larger rev\nenues and Increased prosperity, add\ning that burdensome taxes had been\na great hlndernnce to development\nprogress and prosperity.\nMore Liberal Enrcbase*.\nThe effect of the operation of the\nplan which business men see. If It\nshould be made effective. Is on the\nultimate consumer. They expect tho\nsaving In Income tax to individuals\nwould be translated Into more liberal\npurchases.\nThe 5325,000,000 which Secretary\nMellon States would remain In pos\nsession of the taxpayers and in gen\neral circulation If his policy Is fol\nlowed. is the smallest factor business\nmen see in the situation. What they\nchiefly count upon la the volume of\ncapital which would be released from\ntax-exempt securities to move Into\nIndustrial Investment. Industrial se\ncurities carrying a normal rate of\nInterest have been unable to compete\nIn attractiveness with Investments In\ntax-exempt securities with people of\ngreat wealth.\n<'harles M. Vaughn, president of the\n\u25a0Philadelphia- Chamber of Commerce,\nsays that the relief which those of\nmoderate Incomes would receive from\nthe tax revision would send a fine\nflow of capital into channels from\nwhich- it will reach Industry, and\nmake Industrial and railroad bonds\nmore attraettiv\n\u2022lore funds for Investment.\nTht? railroads and other great basic\nIndustries of the country will be com\npolled to go to the public for funds in\n1924, as they have determined to con\ntinue the tremendous campaigns of\nexpansion and equipment buying of\nthe past year. The release of capital\nunder the tax revision plan, it Is felt\nby railroad men. would provide funds\nfor these expansion programs at a\nmoderate Interest rate.\nThe program of the electric rail\nroads Is even more extensive. E. E.\nl/oomls, president of the Lehigh Val\nley railroad, outlined the attitude of\nthe carriers by asserting that there\nwas a tremendou* opportune for le\ngitimate expansion If taxes could be\nso adjusted as to restore confidence\nand attract capital.\nTEST CASE UP WEDNESDAY\nJudge Announces Next Move in\nyige'ly Wiggly Suit.\nMINEOLA, N. Y., November 16.\nPrank Milton and Walter U Smith\nof Memphis, Tenn., plaintiffs in a\n5100,000 damage suit against tho New\nYork Stock Exchange as an out\ngrowth of the Plggly Wiggly corner\nlast March, have been directed by Su\npreme Court Justice Carswell to show\ncause on November 21 why service\nof a summons on the exchange should\nnot be set aside. The suit was\nbrought to test the legality of the\nauthority of the exchange to post\npone the delivery of stock sold short.\nCounsel for the stock exchange con\ntended that because the organization\nwas not incorporated, the action\nshould be brought against the presi\ndent, treasurer or all the associated\nmembers and that service on the\npresident. Seymour L. Cromwell, was\nnot legal.\nCOMMODITY NEWS\nWIRED STAR FROM\nENTIRE COUNTRY\nKANSAS CITY, Mo., November 17.\nLocal representatives of the Pacific\nFruit and Export Company, owned\njointly by the Southern Pacific and\nUnion Pacific roads, have received\nnotice that the company Is purchas\ning 3,057 refrigerator oars, to be de\nlivered before July 1, 1924.\nBOSTON, November 17.\u2014Receipt* of\ncotton at the five principal consum\ning centers In New England In Octo\nber totaled 89,591 bale*, as against\n09.159 last year. Receipts for the\nseason to date have been 146.468\nbales, as against 125.290 a year ago\nAs a number of mill* had part of\ntheir equipment Idle In October It Is\nbelieved receipts were In excess of\nconsumption.\nDETROIT, November 17.\u2014The ob\nservance of Armistice day had the\neffect of cutting- Ford production thl*\nweek by 616 cars and truck*. The\ntotal turned out was 39,177.\nPITTSBURGH, November It.\u2014Plate\nglass production continues at capac\nity, manufacturers having orders on\ntheir books for months in advance.\nWindow glow demand is not *o\ntlroiig.\nST. IX>UIB, November 17.--Bt, Loul*\nmanufacturers and distributor* In the\nfirst ten month* of this year sold\ncommodities In Cuba to the value of\n98.451,200, the larger portion of which\n\u2022was devoted to dry good* and cloth\ntag.\nSPRINGFIELD, 111., November 17.\n\u2014Tho Illinois white potato crop will\ntotal 10,948,000 bushel* this year, a*\ncompared with 7.449,700 bushels In\n1922. The average yield Is 92 bushels\nan acre, as against 62 last year, the\nb\u00ab\u00bbt since 1915. The oorn crop is\nestimated at 311,877,000 bushels, or\n26,000,000 under last year, with an\naverage yield of 37.5 bushels an acre.\nPORTLAND, Oreg., November 17.\nLargo shipments of prunes In bags\nare now being made to Belgium, local\nshippers having discovered that the\nBelgian customs regulations favor\nrhipments in bags rather than packed\nboxen.\nFINANCIAL.\nNEW YORK CURB MARKET\nReceived by Private Wire Direct to The Star Office\nBY WILLIAM F. HEFPERNAN,\nNEW YORK, November 17.\u2014Indus\ntrial stocks were subjected to more\nselling pressure on the curb market\ntoday than they hod been at any pre\nvious time of the week.\nStandard Oil Pips Line Issues, while\nsomewhat lower, were not as weak\nas they had been.\nDurant of Delaware played a prom\ninent part, breaking over 4 points to\nNEW YORK, November 17. \u2014Follow-\ning Is an official list of bonds and stocks\ntraded in on the New York curb market\ntoday;\nin BONDS.\nHigh. Low. 1:15.\n3 Allied Packer. 8. 67 6614 66%\n3AnTtT 6i 100% 100% 100%\n3 Anaconda 6a 101% 101 101\nlAtOAWIReB, 42% 42% 42%\n2 Bearer board 8. 74 74 74\n2 Beth Steel 7a 35 102% 102% 102%\n6CWft N W Ss W I 98% 08% 08%\n12 Clt Serv 7a D 89 88% 80\n5 Cuban Tel 7%* 105% 106% 106%\n4 Deere Co 7%. 100 09% 100\n2 Dunlop T1 Hub 7. 92 02 02\n5 Federal Sugar 6a '33 98 08 OSU\na Flkher Body 6a '2B 07 OT% 9,%\n1 Gtlr Robl fa 06 06 96\n2 Gen Asphalt 8a 104% 104% I<H%\n1 Gulf Oil of Pa 5a 94% 04% 94%\n6 Hood Rubber 7. 101 101 101\n1 Intern Match 8%*.. 94% 04% 94%\n1 Kan City Term 5%* 100% 100% 100%\n8 Kennecott Cop 7a... 103% 1039 k 193%\n1 Manitoba Pow 7. 98 9\u00ab OH\n1 Morn. &Co 7%. 95% 98% 98%\nB Nat Leather 6a 90% 95%\n1 New Orl Fub Ser 5\u00ab 88%\n1 Phtla 