00\nAmerican Sugar Os 1937 100% 101\nAmerican Tel. A Tel. 6a 1924.. 100% 100%\nAmerican Tel. Tel. 6\u00ab 1925.. 110 110%\nAnaconda Copper 0\u00ab 1029 101 101%\nAnglo-American Oil 7%h 1925.. 101% 102\nBaltimore A Ohio 0s 1924...... 100% 100A,\nCanadian Northern 5%a 1024... 100 100%\nCentral Argentine Rwy. 6s 1927. 07 08%\nCentral Leather 5a 1925 03% 03%\nChi.. B. I. A Pacific 5%s 1020.. 07% 08%\nChicago Tel. 6s 1028 00%\nDu Pont 7%a XKU 106 108%\nEdison Hi. 111. of Boa. o%s 1925. 100% 100%\nFederal Sugar Ref. fls 1933.. v. 07% 98%\nFisher Body Corp. 6* 1027...... 98 98%\nPlsbtl Body Corp. 6* 1928 07 97%\nGoodyear T. ft B. 8* 1931 100% 100%\nGreat Northern 7s 1936 106% 106%\nHocking Valley 6\u00ab 1924 100% 100*\nHumble OH 5%a 1032 06% 97%\nKennecott Copper 7s 1930 108% 104\nLibby. McNeil ft Libby 7a 1931. 99 99%\nMichigan State Tel. 6a 1024 99% 100%\nM*. St. P. ft 8. 8. M. 6%s 1081. 101% 101%\nMorris ft Co. 7* 1030 90 99%\nPenn*. R. B. 7* 1080 107% 107%\nBt Paul Union Depot 5%a 1923. 9914 1009,\nSwift A Co. 5s 1032 01% 01%\nTidewater Oil 6%s 1031 102 2 102%\nUnion Tank Car 7a 1930 103% 104\nV. 8. Rubber 7%\u00bb 1080 108% 104%\nWestern Union B%* 1030....... 109 109%\nWestlnghouse K. AM. 7s 1931. 107% 107%\nBOSTON STOCK MARKET.\nBOSTON, November 17.\u2014Following\nis a list of today\u2019s highest lowest and\nclosing prices for the most active\netook* dealt in here:\nHigh. Low. cioae.\nAm Tel A Tel 123% 123% 123%\nAmoskesg 72% 72%\nArlaona Com 8% 8% 8%\nBoston-Elevated 77% 77% 77%\nCain A Arl* 45 45 46\nOslo A Heel* 18% 18% 18%\nCopper Range 25% 24% 26\nEastern 8 8 *4% 83 B 4\nEdison Elec 156% 165% 155%\nFranklin 1% 1% 1%\nGreenfld Tap A Die 16 15 IB\nHardy Coal 28% 28% 28%\nHood Bobber 63% 58% 58%\nIsland Creek 95% 94% 96%\nIsland Creek pfd 91 91 91\nMaas Gas.... 78% 78% 78%\nMayflower 0 C 2 2 2\nMexican Investment 4 4 4\nMohawk 33 83 86\nNew Cornelia 16 16% 15%\nNY.N H A H 13% 13% 18%\nNorth Butt* 2% 2% 2%\nPacific Mills 86% 86% 86%\nQuincy 22% 2lg 21%\nShannon 60 40 45\nShoe Mach 88% 33 88\nShoe Mach pfd 26% 26% 26%\nSwift A Co 101% 101% 1013\nSwift Internal 17% 17% 1,%\nTuolumne 78 60 75\nUtah Coo 70 70 70\nUtah Metal 40 40 40\nVentura Oil 24 23 28%\nWaldorf 16 16 16\nWalworth 1\u201d% I<% 17%\nWlnone 36 83 35\nTHE EVENING-STAR, WASHINGTON. D. C.. SATURDAY; NOVEMBER 17. 1923.\n20%, the lowest this year, and was\noff over 8 points on the week at 80%.\nUniversal Pipe preferred sold 1%\npoints under Friday\u2019s close.\nVacuum, Prairie Oil and Gas and\nStandard Oil of Indiana were frac\ntionally lower, but Seaboard Oil and\nGas and Southern States. In the In\ndependent group, retained their re\ncent Improvement.\nLone Star Consolidated Mining was\nthe center of Interest in Its group.\nHomestake Extension broke over 20\npoints on rather large offerings.\n7 Reading Coal rta wl 21% 21% 21%\n6 Kepettl Candy 85 .85 .85\n4 Roamcr Motors 6% 6% 6%\n20 So C A 1 new .15 .15 .15\n9 Swift Internal! 17 18% 17\n1 Studebaker Wlf Bb 48% 46% 46%\n22 Tobacco Prod Exp.. 4% 4V* 4%\n1 Todd Ship 46% 46% 46%\n1 Uni Retail Candy.., 5 5 5\n1 D S Lt A Heat 80 .80 .80\n1 U 8 Distribute 25 25 25\n2 Unlv Pipe pfd w t. 65 55 55\n1 Yel Taxi Corn N Y 123% 123% 128%\n505 Wrlgley, W J new. 40% 40% 40%\nMINING.\n4 Alaaka Brlt-Colo .89 .82 .85\n2 Amb Exploration 1% 1% 1%\nCO Arlaona Globe Cop.. .09 .00 .00\n10 Boat Mon Corp D R .17 .17 .17\n0 Canano Copper 1H 1% 1%\n5 Cent Amer 1% 1% 1%\n7 COn* Cop Mas c\u00abw 1% 1% 1%\n60 Cortes Silver 49 .48 .40\n1 Crown King Cons.. 1% 1% 1%\n1 Crown Reserve 60 .60 .60\n270 Fortune Mines 10 .06 -10\n10 Forty Nice Mines,. .18 .18 .18\nSO Goldfield Deep Minas .07 .07 .07\n10 Gold Held Florence... .48 .48 .48\n111 Goldfield Jackpot .43 .43 .43\n140 Gold Zone 00 .00\n20 11111 Toil Nevada... .03 .03 .03\n26 liomesteko Ext .75 .62 .75\n2 Howe Sound 2% 2% 2%\n40 Independence Lead. .24 .28 .24\n3210 Lone Star 12 .08 .12\nI Mason Valley 1% 1% 1%\n110 National Tin .19 .12 .13\n7 New Dominion Cop. 2% 2% 2%\n1 New Jersey Zinc. 143% 145% 143%\n18 N Y Porcupine .75 .74 .75\n20 Nevada 81l Horn .01 .01 .01\n2o Nixon Nevada 01 .01 .01\nIX Ohio Copper 83 .84 .85\nCO Red Hill Florence. .03 .04 .04\n116 Kt Croix Mine .57 .90\n60 Silver Horn Min... .08 .07 .07\n30 Silver Pick 06 06 .06\n70 Spearhead Cold .OR .06 .08\n40 Tonopah Beimout .37 .35 .36\n3 Tonopah Divide .49 .49 .49\n5 'i'nsopah Min 1% 1% 1%\n3 Uni Eastern I,'v Its JtV\n10 Us Contin new wl .18 .18 .16\n36 Wenden Cop .95 .9.1 .95\n3 West End Con* .68 .68 .68\n10 White Caps 07 .07 .01\n1 White Knok Cop pf .55 .65 .65\n1 Yukon Gold 70 .70 .70\non\nCAREJNBUSINESS\nFake Optimism of Today\nDangerous, He Tells\nD. C. Leaders.\n\u201cThe need of the hour is to cut our\nfake optimism and false standards\nand return to old-fashioned honesty,\nindustry, thrift and service,\" declared\nRoger XV. Babson at a meeting of tho\nBabson Statistical Organization yester\nday at the New Willard Hotel under\nthe auspices of the Merchants and\nManufacturers\u2019 Association.\n\u201cThere never was a time when\nAmericans were so divided as to the\nbusiness outlook. This very fact,\nhowever, should cause you successful\nbusiness men to take your task very\nseriously during the next few\nmonths.\u201d he said, urging his hearers\nto \u201ccut out frills, collect your bills,\nkeep down inventories, reduce costs,\navoid getting into more debt and get\nout of debt as fast as possible.\"\n\u201cWe must all work together for\nlower taxes, greater confidence, more\nefficiency and fundamental rather\nthan superficial remedies,\u201d he de\nclared. He said great cake should be\nexercised to prevent unemployment\nand poor business in 1924.\nFCars Europe** Situation.\nDescribing the European situation\nand the maintenance of large armies\nas a reason for watchfulness over\nbusiness conditions here, Mr. Babson\ndeclared, \u201cSomething will break ulti\nmately. Europe will either disarm\nor fight.\u201d While he held that an\nother European war would temporari\nly help business here, it would mean\nthe bankruptcy of Europe, with harm\nful results later.\nFour other reasons were cited by\nMr. Babson for business care.\nThis year is developing unsatisfac\ntorily for producers of coal, oils, cop\nper, leather, rubber, wheat and many\nother basic raw materials.\nThe tremendous amount spent on\nautomobiles makes it impossible Tor\npeople to buy other things.\nThe presidential election, with very\nradical groups in both parties. Indi\ncations of a drive against the rail\nroads In Congress, with harmful re\nsults on the stock market and the la\nbor and farm situation were also In\ncluded in this heading.\nThe attitude toward life on the part\nof many who desire merely to be tak\nen care of by their governments, fed\nand amused.\nMaj. Gen. Anton Stephan, president\nof the Merchants and Manufacturers'\nAssociation, Introduced the speaker.\nBUTTER PRICES FIRM.\nCHICAGO, November 17.\u2014Impor\ntant changes In either prices or con\nditions were lacking in the butter\nmarket during the week. Under\ngrades weakened at Chicago and\nI'hiladelphla. and at New York and\nBoston undergrade prices advanced\nto a point more in line with Chicago.\nClosing prices and rang*. 92 score\nbutter, at the four principal markets\nfollow:\nChicago, unchanged at 51%; New\nYork, 1 higher at 53%; Boston, un\nchanged at 51%, and Philadelphia,\n1 higher at 53%.\nBUILDING CONTRACTS UP.\nPHILADELPHIA, Pa., November 17\n(Special).\u2014Building contracts let In\nthis city last month amounted to\n16.486.100, an Increase of 35 per cent\nover the preceding month and of 6\nper cent over October, 1922. These\ncontracts Included $3,624,500 for\ndwellings, $1,222,000 for business\nstructures and $864,800 for factories.\nThe total amount of building started\nin the first ten months of this year\naggregated $81,418,900, or 21 per cent\nless than for the corresponding period\nof 1922.\nPASSENGER TRAFFIC GROWS.\nATLANTA, November 17 (Special)\n\u2014The street railways of this city are\ncarrying 260,000 more passengers\neach month than they did in 1922, ac\ncording to reports Just filed with the\nGeorgia public service commission.\nPARIS MARKET SPOTTY.\nPARIS. November 17.\u2014Prices moved\nirregularly on the bourse today. Three\nper cent rentes 38 francs 26 centimes\nExchange on London, 81 francs 60\ncentimes. Five per cent loan, 69\nfrancs 10 centimes. The dollar was\nquoted at 18 francs 98% centimes.\nWOOL PRICES FIRM.\nBOSTON, November 17 (Special).\u2014\nBoston raw wool markets closed the\nweek on an optimistic note with the\nlower grade wools moving In good\nquantities and with many dealers pre\ndicting an early increase in the de\nmand for better grades. Prices were\nslightly firmer.\nRED FIELD TO SPEAK.\nNEW YORK,'November 17.\u2014Former\nSecretary of Commerce William C.\nRedfleld will be the principal speaker\nat the luncheon meeting of the Broad\nway Association on Tuesday at the\nHotel Astor. George I* Slawson will\npreside.\nMUCH SWITCHING 1\nTO RAILSTOCKS\nindustrials Forfeit Part of\nRecent Gains During Week.\nCoppers Active.\nBy the Associated Ptm.\nNEW YORK, November 17.\u2014Switch\ning of speculative interest from the\nIndustrial to the railroad shares was\none of the features of this week'*\nstock market, which continued to ig\nnore the unfavorable political devel\nopments abroad. Demand sterling\nand all the principal continental ex\nchanges collapsed to new low levels\nfop the year in response to the dis\nsolution of parliament and the aban\ndonment of the proposed reparations\nconference.\nIndustrial Issues, which had been\nbid up rapidly since October 31. for\nfeited part of their gains on profit\ntaking and a renewal of bear selling,\nbut the recognised leaders offered\ngood resistance to selling pressure,\nthe widest breaks taking place in the\nspecialties.\nOil Skarf. Held Their Own.\nThe further reduction in unfilled\norders of the United States Steel Cor\nporation was counteracted to some\nextent by the activity in the pig Iron\nmarket and the Increasing inquiries\nregarding new business. Oils were\nInclined to Improve on the further\nreduction In crude oil production, al\nthough the extension of the gasoline\nprice-cutting war to the eastern sea\nboard and further downward read\njustment In crude prices had a sorae\nwhnt depressing effect on some shares.\nCoppers were bought on the strength\nof the quarterly statements of the\nporphyry companies and the reports\nthat sales of the red metal in the\nfirst two weeks of this month had ex\nceeded 200,000,000 pounds. Heavy\nproduction schedules for next spring\nannounced by some of the larger au\ntomobile companies brought fresh\nbuying Into the motor and motor ac\ncessory stocks.\nCrap Report Help* Buying.\nMall order and farm Implement Is\nsues benefited by Secretary Wallace's\nstatement that the value of eleven\nprincipal crops had Increased from\n35,200.000,000 In l#il to about 17,000,-\n000.000 this year. Indicating Increased\npurchasing power of the farmer.\nWHEAT\u00ae*\nDROP DING WEEK\nGrain Traders Scared by\nSharp Break in British Ex\nchange\u2014Lard Prices Firm.\nBy the Associated Pn\u00ab\n\u2022CHICAGO. November 17. Wheat\nprices have gone down hill this week\nhand In hand with foreign exchange.\nSuccessive new low records for ster\nling. In particular, had a decided\nbearish effect. Compared with a\nweek ago, wheat this morning was la\n1% to 3H down, com 2% to 3\u00ab4 off,\noats at H&H to decline, and pro\nvisions varying from a 13 setback to\n30 advance.\nSpreading operations, selling of\nwheat here against simultaneous buy\ning in Winnipeg, attracted special\nattention during the week.\nPredictions that receipts of corn\nwould become larger and that de\nmand for feeding would be curtailed\npulled down the com markets. Oats\nwere easier with com.\nScarcity of lard here gave firmness\nto that commodity, but other provi\nsions were weak, owing to excessive\narrivals of hogs.\nPAR CLEARANCE IS\nBLAMED BY BANKER\nGiven as Reason Why Many\nBanks Stay Out of Fed\neral Reserve.\nBy the Associated Praia.\nATLANTA, Ga.. November 17.\u2014Par\nclearance was again given as the\nmain reason for the failure of eligi\nble state banks to come Into the\nfederal reserve system at the hearing\nby a joint congressional committee\nhere yesterday.\nClarification by congress of the ex\nchange provisions of the federal re\nserve was recommended by John K.\nOttley, president of the Fourth Na\ntional Bank of this city. Represen\ntative Wingo of Arkansas, In dis\ncussing Mr. Ottley\u2019s proposal, said\nhe believed such an attempt would\nmeet fatal opposition in the Senate,\nwhere he declared the notion pre\nvails that the country banker Is a\nperson expected to render service to\nthe city banker and the wholesaler.\nLimited return from investment or\ncost of membership also was cited by\nMr. Ottley as a reason for the state\nbanks\u2019 not joining the reserve system.\nIn this connection Representative\nLewis T. McFadden of Pennsylvania,\nchairman of the committee, suggested\nthat larger distribution of earnings\namong member banks would be tan\ntamount to putting the federal re\nserve system Into competition with\nmember banks. This was not Mr.\nOttley\u2019s view, he said.\nREFUSAL TO BARE COSTS\nBARS RIGHT TO IMPORT\nTreasury to Deny Singer Manu\nfacturing Company Bights to Use\nCustoms for One Tear.\nForeign manufacturers who refuse\nto submit for examination their\nbooks on production cost may be\ndenied the right to Import for one\nyear, according to Information sent\nout yesterday to customs officers by\nthe Treasury.\nThe power authorised in section\n610 of the tariff act may thus be in\nvoked for the first time. Instructions\nwere sent to customs collectors by\nAssistant Secretary Mou with an\nopinion by Attorney General Daugh\nerty saying the Treasury's authority\nwas absolute. The opinion referred\ndirectly to shipments by the Singer\nManufacturing Company, Limited, of\nClydebank. Scotland, and declared\nthat denial by the company of the\ninspection privilege constituted valid\ngrounds for use of the provision to\nclose the customshouse\u2019 doors to the\nconcern for one year.\nDIVIDENDS.\nPay- Stock of\nCompany. Period. Rate. nbla. Record.\nBk. of Nora Scotia. O 4% Jan. 2 Dec. IS\nCrucible Steel pf... O IS% Dec. 81 Dec. 15\nCent Iron Pipe 80c Dee. 20 Dec. 6\nCrfet Iron Pipe pf 60c Dec. 80 Dec. 6\nChesebr. Mfg. 8p 33.00 Dee. 28 Dee. 10\nCheabrongh Mfg Q as.so Pec. 28 Dec. 10\nChesbr. Mfg. pf.... Q 31.75 Dec. 28 Dec. 10\nMengel Co. pf.... Q I\\% Dec. 1 Nor. 80\nTex Golf Sulphur. Q 31.30 Dec. 15 Dec I\n\nMarkets Appear to Doubt Break\nBettveen England and France\nReparations Likely to Hold Nations\nTogether\u2014Strength in Cotton and\nDrop in Wheat Support View\nBY STUART P. WEST.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Btar.\nNEW YORK, November 17.\u2014The\nmatter of primary Interest at tho\nclose of the week Is the probable\npractical effect upon political and\nfinancial conditions of a break be\ntween Englan'd and France on tho\nquestion of European policy.\nNobody Is able to put forth more\nthan a conjecture, but two things\nstand out clearly. The first Is that\nsuch rupture would still further\nindefinitely postpone the settlement\nof German reparations, and therefore\nindefinitely delay the restoration of\nEurope. The second is that the mar\nkets have not given the conventional\nsigns that would Indicate fear of\nserious consequences.\nIt Ss true that there has been a\ndemoralised decline in the foreign, ex\nchanges, carrying them to much the\nlowest of the year, and it Is true\nthat French and Belgian government\nsecurities have been under severe\npressure. But the other phenomena of\na war scare have not appeared. A\nviolent upturn in wheat is one of the\nfirst traditional signals of Impending\ntrouble, and wheat prices within the\nlast day or two have been making\nnew lows for the season.\nThe rule is that political disorders\nabroad should cause lower prices for\ncotton, in that they suggest the pos\nsibility of a shutdown in the foreign\ndemand; But cotton has kept on mak\ning new high records. Similarly, the\nstationary tendency of money rates\nand the firmness of investment se\ncurities are two further bits of tes\ntimony that there is not as yet any\nreal uneasiness.\nDecline of Exchange*.\nThe decline in the exchanges i*\ndue to a number of causes, the rela\ntive importance of which le the sub\nject of widely differing opinion. The\nsterling market has been peculiarly\nsensitive because the political com\nplications came at a time when Great\nBritain was preparing to meet the\nnext installment on the American\nwar debt, when large sums were due\non high-priced American cotton and\nwhen the approaching election was\nCasting Its shadow over *ll English\nmarkets. Had it not been for this\nunfortunate combination it is diffi\ncult to believe that the disturbing\ndevelopments in European politics\nwould have caused any such\ndecline. Sterling has stood up *ll\nalong because the collection of\nGreat Britain\u2019s 22 per cent of the\ntotal indemnity assessed against Ger\nmany was not vital to British finance.\nEngland was able without any in\ndemnity money to balance its budget,\nreduce taxes and begin payments to\ntho United States.\nFrench Attitude May Change.\nTho position la wholly different in\ntho case of France. Here the budget\nis not being balanced except by a\nconstant piling up of the already\nhuge internal debt. The theory Iff\nthat these domestic loans will sooner\nor later bo paid off with German\nreparations and that tho French\npeasant Investor will be patient\nundor the load in tho meantime.\nIt is confidence In this which causes\nFrench statesmen to stand outagainet\nthe united governments of the world,\nand there seems to be no reason to\nhope for any change In their atti\ntude unless the franc continues to\ndepreciate. Increasing the already\nhigh cost of living to the French. It\nis conceivable that such pressure\nwould cause proper recognition of\nwhat has been demonstrated for the\nlast ten months, that It is impossible\nto collect reparations at the point of\nthe bayonet, and that the true Inter\nest of France, os of- the rest of the\nworld, are in putting Germany on\nher feet.\nThe more immediate aspect of the\nbreak- in the exchanges which has\nbeen general all over Europe, 1* that\nthe latest political crisis has made\nholders of foreign currencies feel\nlike selling out and transferring to\nAmerican dollars.\nRival View* *a Baal mesa Outlook.\nOur own security markets, while\nmore or less affected by the occur\nrences abroad, have had their atten\ntion fixed mainly upon the business\noutlook at home. The recovery of\nthe first two week* of November put\nprices back to a reasonable level after\nthe depression of the early autumn.\nThe general run of Blocks were satis\nfied with this, and settled down to a\nDefies of small fluctuations, the theory'\nbeing that it was well to wait until a\nbetter line could be obtained upon\nbusiness conditions In 192*.\nOn this subject there are two rival\nsets of opinion. One believes that the\nsatisfactory, and indeed very large,\nvolume of general trade will be main\ntained, because there is no prospect\nof wages coming down and employ\nment diminishing, hence no likeli\nhood of a let-up In the general buy-\nFirst Mortgage Loans\nLowest Bate* of Interest sad Commlaaloa.\nPrompt Action\nThomas J. Fisher St Company, Inc.\n788 16th street\nJVTnTiBWTr~TM\nMargin of Security I\nWe Demand to Safeguard B\nClients Investing In Our I\n7%\nFirst Mortgage Note*\nInsures ebeolete safety under any and all\ncondition*.\nIt\nUpbeMe alee our established tecord of\nsever bavin* lost In either principal or\ninterest as much as a alngla penny.\nGuaranteed tltlaa and Insurance policies\nfurnished with all note*.\nNotes of SIM, $250, op to $5,000\nNow on Hand\nFor fall particular* apply to Mr.\nO\u2019Donnell. Loan Department\nCHAS. D. SA